  <!-- Section: Common Mistakes -->
  <section id="mistakes" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Common Mistakes to Avoid</h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Not Joining Mutualiteit Within 3 Months</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">You must join a mutualiteit within 3 months of starting work. Missing this deadline can cause issues with healthcare access and compliance. Your employer registers you with ONSS, but YOU must choose and join a mutualiteit yourself.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Missing the Expat Tax Regime Deadline</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">The special expat tax regime (30% exclusion) must be applied for within 6 months of starting work. Your employer must file. Missing this deadline means losing significant tax benefits for your entire Belgian assignment. Verify with your employer immediately.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Underestimating Processing Times</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Belgium's Single Permit can take 3-4 months from application to work authorization. Don't resign your current job expecting to start quickly. Brussels is particularly slow. Plan start dates accordingly and communicate with your employer about realistic timelines.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Not Registering at Commune Within 8 Days</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">You must register at your local gemeente/commune within 8 working days of arrival. Missing this can delay your residence card and create administrative problems. Book an appointment immediately—some communes have waiting times.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Assuming Salary Includes Threshold</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">The €47,703 highly skilled threshold is gross annual salary. Verify your contract shows this amount. Some offers quote net or monthly amounts that don't meet the threshold when calculated annually. Falling below means labor market test applies.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: Healthcare in Belgium -->
  <section id="healthcare" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Healthcare in Belgium</h2>

    <p class="mb-4">
      Belgium has excellent healthcare with short wait times and high quality. The system is based on reimbursement through mutualiteiten—you pay upfront and claim back ~75%. Most care is provided by private practitioners and hospitals operating within the public insurance framework.
    </p>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">How Belgian Healthcare Works</h3>

    <div class="space-y-4 mb-6">
      <div class="border-l-4 border-primary-500 pl-4">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">General Practitioners</h4>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Choose any GP (huisarts/médecin généraliste). Pay ~€30-40 per visit, claim back ~€25 from mutualiteit. Your cost: ~€5-15 per visit. No registration required—you can see any doctor.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-primary-500 pl-4">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Specialists</h4>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Referral not required—see specialists directly. Costs vary (€50-150). Reimbursement ~75%. Wait times are short—typically days to weeks, not months. Brussels has many English-speaking specialists.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-primary-500 pl-4">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Hospitals</h4>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Mix of public and private hospitals. Emergency care (spoedgevallen/urgences) is free at point of use. For planned care, you pay room supplements unless you have hospitalization insurance. Major hospitals in Brussels, Leuven, Ghent are excellent.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-primary-500 pl-4">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Pharmacies (Apotheek/Pharmacie)</h4>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Prescription medications are partially covered. You pay a portion (remgeld) and mutualiteit covers the rest. Night and weekend pharmacies operate on rotation. Many pharmacists speak English in Brussels.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Finding English-Speaking Doctors</h3>

    <p class="mb-4">
      In Brussels, English is widely spoken by healthcare providers due to the international community. In Flanders, English is common; in Wallonia, French dominates. Use doctoranytime.be or your mutualiteit's doctor finder to search by language.
    </p>

    <div class="bg-blue-50 border border-blue-200 rounded-lg p-4">
      <p class="text-blue-800">
        <strong>Third-party payment (derdebetalersregeling):</strong> Some providers offer "third-party payment" where you only pay your share (remgeld) and the provider claims directly from your mutualiteit. This reduces upfront costs. Ask your doctor if they offer "derdebetalersregeling."</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: FAQ -->
  <section id="faq" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What's the difference between mutualiteit and health insurance?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Mutualiteit is Belgium's social security health coverage—mandatory for all residents. It reimburses ~75% of healthcare costs. Private health insurance (hospitalization) is optional and covers the remaining costs plus extras like private hospital rooms. Everyone needs mutualiteit; hospitalization insurance is additional.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">How do I qualify for the expat tax regime?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          You must be recruited from abroad, have specialized skills, and not have been a Belgian tax resident in the prior 5 years. Salary typically €75,000+ (varies). Your employer must apply within 6 months of start date. If approved, 30% of salary is tax-free as "cost allowance." Very valuable—verify eligibility with employer immediately.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Do I need to speak Dutch or French?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          In Brussels, English is sufficient for most international roles. In Flanders, Dutch is increasingly expected for integration (though English works initially). In Wallonia, French is essential. For EU institutions and international organizations, English is the working language.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">How long until permanent residence?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          After 5 years of legal residence, you can apply for permanent residence (long-term resident status). This provides indefinite stay rights and is not tied to employment. Citizenship is possible after 5 years with language and integration requirements.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can I change employers on the Single Permit?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          The Single Permit is tied to your employer. To change jobs, you need a new Single Permit application with the new employer. Processing is usually faster for renewals/changes than initial applications. You can work for the new employer once the new permit is approved.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can my family join me?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Yes. Spouse and children can apply for family reunification. They'll need to show your relationship, your income (sufficient to support family), and housing. Spouses receive work authorization. Process takes 6-9 months typically. Apply after your own permit is confirmed.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: Final Verdict -->
  <section id="verdict" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Final Verdict</h2>

    <p class="mb-4">
      Belgium offers unique opportunities as the EU capital, with access to international organizations, multinational headquarters, and a central European location. The Single Permit system is straightforward for highly skilled workers (€47,703+ salary), though processing times can be slow. The expat tax regime provides significant benefits for qualifying roles.
    </p>

    <p class="mb-4">
      Healthcare through the mutualiteit system is affordable (€100-150/year membership) but works on reimbursement—you pay first and claim back ~75%. Most expats add hospitalization insurance for comprehensive coverage. The system is good once you understand it, but different from countries with direct-payment insurance.
    </p>

    <p class="mb-6">
      Brussels is genuinely international with English widely accepted. Flanders and Wallonia require more language adaptation. For EU institution roles, international organization work, or multinational positions, Belgium is hard to beat. Plan for 3-4 month processing times and verify expat tax regime eligibility early.
    </p>

    <div class="bg-primary-50 border border-primary-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-primary-900 mb-3">Bottom Line</h3>
      <p class="text-primary-800 mb-4">
        Belgium's Single Permit is accessible for highly skilled workers (€47,703+). Mutualiteit membership is mandatory and affordable; add hospitalization insurance for full coverage. Processing is slow—plan ahead. The expat tax regime (30% exclusion) is valuable—apply within 6 months. Ideal for EU institution and international organization careers.
      </p>
